## Why This Is Asked
Tests memory ownership and boundary safety when mixing Go and C. Candidates must implement correct allocation/free on the C side and valid binding in Go, ensuring no Go pointers cross into C and that allocations are freed.

## Key Concepts
- CGO memory ownership across boundaries
- CGO pointer rules: avoid passing Go pointers to C
- Concurrency safety with CGO calls
- Leak prevention via paired malloc/free

## Code Example
```c
// cg_seq.h
int* generate_seq(int n);
void free_seq(int* p);
```

```go
// go_bind.go
/*
#cgo CFLAGS: -I.
#include "cg_seq.h"
*/
import "C"

func GenerateSeq(n int) *C.int { return C.generate_seq(C.int(n)) }
func FreeSeq(p *C.int) { C.free_seq(p) }
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you return the length safely alongside the pointer?
- How to detect leaks in tests with tools like valgrind or Go race detector?

