## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to bridge Go and C with callbacks across threads, a common real-world CGO pitfall. It probes lifetime management, thread-safety, and CGO pointer rules.

## Key Concepts
- CGO callback lifetimes and //export limitations
- cg oHandle usage to store Go values for C callbacks
- Thread-safety: mutexes and safe dispatch of callbacks
- Proper cleanup to avoid leaks when unregistering

## Code Example
```javascript
// C header (capi.h)
typedef void (*cb_t)(int eventCode, void* context);
void register_cb(cb_t cb, void* ctx);
void emit_event(int code);
```

```javascript
// Go binding (cgowa/cgo) - simplified
package main
/*
#include "capi.h"
*/
import "C"
import (
  "sync"
  "unsafe"
)

var (
  mu       sync.Mutex
  cbStore  = map[uintptr]func(int){}
  nextKey  uintptr = 1
)

//export goCallback
func goCallback(event C.int, ctx unsafe.Pointer) {
  mu.Lock()
  if f, ok := cbStore[uintptr(ctx)]; ok {
    f(int(event))
  }
  mu.Unlock()
}

func registerCallback(f func(int)) unsafe.Pointer {
  mu.Lock()
  key := nextKey
  nextKey++
  cbStore[key] = f
  mu.Unlock()
  // pass key as ctx to C
  return unsafe.Pointer(uintptr(key))
}
```

```javascript
// Minimal usage (main.go)
package main
import (
  "C"
  "fmt"
)
func main(){
  cb := func(e int){ fmt.Println("event:", e) }
  ctx := registerCallback(cb)
  C.emit_event(42) // would trigger goCallback with ctx
  _ = ctx
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
