- How do you handle panics in Go callbacks so they don’t crash the C caller or CGO bridge?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests memory ownership, error propagation, and CGO threading. It verifies that the candidate safely consumes C-allocated data, prevents leaks, and handles non-thread-safe C APIs in Go.

## Key Concepts
- CGO memory management and ownership transfer
- Error handling from C to Go
- Thread-safety and mutex usage for non-thread-safe C calls
- Avoiding Go pointers in C and ensuring proper lifetimes
- Resource finalization patterns

## Code Example
```go
package main

/*
typedef struct { int code; const char* msg; } ScanResult;
ScanResult* perform_scan(const char* query);
void free_scan_result(ScanResult*);
*/
import "C"
import (
  "errors"
  "sync"
  "unsafe"
)

var scanMu sync.Mutex

func Scan(query string) (string, error) {
  cQuery := C.CString(query)
  defer C.free(unsafe.Pointer(cQuery))

  scanMu.Lock()
  defer scanMu.Unlock()

  res := C.perform_scan(cQuery)
  if res == nil {
    return "", errors.New("nil ScanResult from C")
  }
  defer C.free_scan_result(res)

  if res.code != 0 {
    msg := C.GoString(res.msg)
    return "", fmt.Errorf("scan failed code=%d: %s", res.code, msg)
  }
  out := C.GoString(res.msg)
  return out, nil
}
```

